{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17507343","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17507343"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:52:50+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:52:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2626"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2626","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2626"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.24,0.07,0.47,0.15,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2626"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"47875"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2626","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2626"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2626"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"32618"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"29"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"1598"},{"type":"tags","id":"2943"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"},{"type":"tags","id":"10977"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2933"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2943"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11645"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12784"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43198"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"47875","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/47875"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-month history of low-grade fever, malaise, shortness of breath on exertion and dry cough. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears cachectic with vital signs within normal limits. Chest X-ray shows bilateral symmetrical, egg-shaped opacities at the hilum. Interferon Gamma Release Assay (IGRA) is negative.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHemoglobin 102 g/L (125\u2013165)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMCV 88 fL (80-100)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWBC 10.9 x 10^9/L (4.0-11.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECreatinine 80 \u00b5mol/L (50 \u2013 120)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECalcium 3.05 mmol/L (2.10-2.55)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAngiotensin-converting enzyme (ACE) 118 U/L (\u0026lt;52)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Given the most likely diagnosis, other than the respiratory system, which of the following organ systems is most commonly involved?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Liver","Nervous system","Skin","Heart","Eyes"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis presentation is most consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Esarcoidosis\u003C/strong\u003E. Sarcoidosis is an inflammatory condition characterised by the formation of granulomas, which can accumulate in multiple organ systems. It most commonly develops between the ages of 20 to 40. The diagnosis is generally made after chest X-rays, CT, a biopsy of granulomas, and various blood tests.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPrevalence of different organ involvement in sarcoidosis includes:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELungs : 89-99% - including intra-thoracic lymph nodes\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESkin: 16-32%\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEyes: 5-23%\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELiver: 12-20%\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPeripheral lymph nodes: 13-15%\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESpleen: 5-10%\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENervous system: 3-9%\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHeart: 2-5%\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Elungs\u003C/strong\u003E are the most common organ involved in sarcoidosis. It causes inflammation that can lead to scarring and progressive worsening of lung function and cor pulmonale (right-sided heart failure). A common presentation of the disease is a cough or shortness of breath.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOf the options available, \u003Cstrong\u003Eskin\u003C/strong\u003E is the next most common organ involved in sarcoidosis. Skin lesions in sarcoidosis include lupus pernio papules, nodules, plaques and infiltrated scars and tattoos. Lupus pernio papules does not pose a health risk but can be associated with psychological distress.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELiver\u003C/strong\u003E involvement in sarcoidosis frequently present with abdominal pain and deranged liver function tests. However, the presentation of hepatic sarcoidosis can range from asymptomatic to severe complications such as cirrhosis and portal hypertension.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELymph nodes \u003C/strong\u003Eparticularly the intra-thoracic cavity can also be commonly affected and visualised on chest x-rays as well-defined bilateral mediastinal and hilar lymphadenopathy. The degree of lymph node calcification is correlated to the disease duration of sarcoidosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeurological\u003C/strong\u003E involvement in sarcoidosis is termed \u0022neurosarcoidosis.\u0022 Areas affected include the cranial nerves, meninges, brain parenchyma, spinal cord, hypothalamus-neurohypophyseal system and peripheral nerves. It can present with headache, facial nerve palsy, trigeminal neuralgia, vertigo, hearing loss, visual loss, gait disturbances, paresis, and paraesthesia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECardiac\u003C/strong\u003E involvement is not commonly observed. Cardiac sarcoidosis can occur in the absence of pulmonary or systemic involvement. It can present with arrhythmia, dyspnoea, fatigue and syncope. Given the high mortality associated with ventricular arrhythmias, heart block and progressive heart failure, early diagnosis and treatment is critical.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEye \u003C/strong\u003Einvolvement in sarcoidosis can present with dry eyes, painful and red eyes and can cause uveitis, glaucoma and vision loss. Uveitis secondary to sarcoidosis is most prevalent in Black and Asian demographics with a prevalence of 10-30%.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The most common organ system affected by sarcoidosis is the lungs","Other organ systems affected include skin, eyes, liver, lymph node, spleen, nervous system and heart"],"references":["Grunewald, J., Grutters, J.C., Arkema, E.V. et al. Sarcoidosis. Nat Rev Dis Primers. 2019 Jul 5;45. https://doi.org/10.1038/s41572-019-0096-x","Sedki M, Fonseca N, Santiago P, Diaz L, Garcia-Buitrago M, Mirsaeidi M, Levy C. Hepatic Sarcoidosis: Natural History and Management Implications. Front Med (Lausanne). 2019 Oct 30;6:232."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"32618"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2626"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"32618","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/32618"},"attributes":